<TEXT>
a bottlenose dolphin that died after 
swimming up the east and hudson rivers was infected by a parasite 
that apparently affected its sense of direction an autopsy revealed 
the dolphin which attracted the interest of marine experts and 
the public for three weeks was an 8foot 600pound female that had 
given birth to at least 12 calves in more than 30 years in the 
atlantic ocean biologists said monday 
as far as dolphins go i think she had a pretty good life it 
was a long one anyway said samuel sadove a marine biologist who 
conducted the autopsy sadove director of the okeanos ocean 
research foundation said dolphins have been known to live 37 years 
the ultimate cause of death was a cerebral hemorrhage the body 
was found sunday in the hudson 
there was no immediate indication that pollution or any toxic 
chemicals contributed to the death sadove said but he added that 
further tissue tests were planned 
the dolphin was first noticed june 20 in the east river between 
manhattan and long island it stayed in the river for about 11 days 
then headed into the hudson and upriver two weeks ago it was 
sighted as far north as kingston more than 80 miles upriver from 
new york harbor 
the dolphin had been infected two or three months ago by a worm 
ingested with infected food sadove said the parasite lodged in the 
sinuses causing a disease called nasitroma which is common in 
marine mammals he said 
the parasite invaded the brain possibly affecting the animals 
sense of direction and environment sadove said 
in addition there were signs of severe stress from being in 
fresh water but returning the animal to the sea would not have 
saved it sadove said 
