<TEXT>
the air force says pilots and air crews will be 
allowed to wear soft contact lenses because they can improve 
eyesight under combat conditions 
pilots and crews in fighter attack and reconnaissance aircraft 
as well as instructor pilots and those whose duty requires the use 
of night vision goggles will be issued the lenses said a statement 
issued monday at the pentagon 
as in the past new pilots will be required to prove they have 
perfect or 2020 vision said a spokeswoman for the air force 
surgeon general 
but if a pilot or crew members vision worsens after they have 
completed their training and it can be corrected to the 2020 
level he or she will be allowed to use either spectacles or the 
soft contact lenses said spokeswoman patti turner 
now its their choice ms turner said 
the new policy is effective immediately she said 
a statement issued at the pentagon said soft lenses have been 
shown to improve the combat capability of some us air force crew 
members who require vision correcting lenses 
their use has been proven to provide an operational advantage 
over the wear of spectacles in missions which require maneuvering 
flight the use of night vision goggles the constant wear of an 
oxygen mask and the ability to quickly look to the far limits of 
lateral gaze the statement said 
ms turner said pilots and aircrews will only be allowed to use 
extendedwear lenses since those are better suited to the 
conditions crews will encounter 
however the lenses will not be allowed to be worn around the 
clock or when sleeping ms turner said nor will tinted or 
disposable types of lenses be allowed 
also those who choose to use the lenses must keep their glasses 
at hand in the event that they encounter a problem or lose one she 
added 
while only certain fliers will be issued the lenses others will 
be able to purchase them through civilian eye care specialists after 
the approval of their flight surgeon the statement said 
army spokeswoman paige eversole said helicopter and fixedwing 
pilots are still not allowed to use contact lenses although that 
matter is being studied 
</TEXT>
