<TEXT>
the solidarity movement welcomed george 
bush to its birthplace today as the president acknowledged the 
decades of workers courage and bloodshed that helped bring about 
polands dramatic move toward democracy 
solidarity greets the president of the usa read a huge 
redandwhite banner hung near solidarity square outside the lenin 
shipyard where the soviet blocs first independent trade union was 
founded in 1980 
twentyfive thousand poles including solidarity members from 
chapters across the country gathered at the towering workers 
monument at the yards gate to hear bush speak 
they chanted long live bush and when the president suggested 
young poles stay in their homeland instead of emigrating they 
chorused stay with us 
if only poland could have such a president said jan panchek 
91 a retired farmer who arrived hours early to glimpse bush 
now bankrupt and awaiting a possible bailout by polishamerican 
businesswoman barbara piasecka johnson the shipyard is the spirtual 
home of solidarity as recently as last august it was the scene of 
strikes that galvanized the nation 
by visiting the yard and lunching at the home of solidarity 
chief lech walesa bush planned a symbolic gesture to the workers 
whose battles with communist authorities in 1970 1980 and 1988 kept 
alive the nations aspirations for greater freedom and a better life 
the shipyard dating to the 19th century was rebuilt after world 
war ii as an industrial showcase of the newly created polish 
peoples state it turned out dozens of ships a year mainly for the 
soviet union 
workers from around the country usually from peasant 
backgrounds were attracted by its relatively high wages and promise 
of technical training one such worker in the late 1960s was a young 
man from the village of popowo lech walesa 
dingy cramped housing and hazardous working conditions soon 
created tensions among this new elite and a round of sharp price 
increases just before christmas 1970 set off strikes all along the 
baltic coast 
outside the gates of the yard security forces opened fire on 
marching workers killing several hundreds are believed to have 
died in the strikes an event that remains etched on the national 
consciousness the official death count was 45 
when solidarity arose in 1980 one of its first demands was to 
erect a monument to the victims of 1970 the 42meter sculpture of 
three crosses and anchors was designed and built by the shipyard 
workers themselves 
it remained an embarrassing reminder to the government during the 
years after the december 1981 martiallaw crackdown when solidarity 
was banned but struggled on as an illegal organization 
authorities claimed solidarity was dead except for a few thousand 
diehards but the union kept up a vibrant underground structure 
waves of strikes in may and august 1988 demonstrated solidarity 
was still very much alive in exchange for ending the august unrest 
authorities resumed negotiations with walesa 
that led to the legalization of solidarity and to last months 
elections in which unionbacked candidates won all but one of the 
261 seats they were allowed to contest 
union organizing took second place to the election campaign and 
leaders concede they have signed up only a fraction of their former 
strength of 10 million between 1 million and 2 million members 
solidarity now must contend with a number of painful new 
challenges 
polands need to reform the crisisridden economy into a 
competitive marketoriented structure could require closing 
outmoded and inefficient factories where solidarity members work 
and eliminating state subsidies for meat milk and other staples 
will bring steep price increases 
