<DOCNO> AP890711-0107 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
defense secretary dick cheney acknowledging he 
has no quick fix for streamlining the pentagon today put 
forward a complex plan to overhaul the military bureaucracy and 
tighten controls over weapons purchases 
he predicted that some 30 billion in total savings could be 
achieved by the 1993 fiscal year if his simplified and more 
efficient weapons acquisition system is put in place 
procurement accounts for more than 60 billion of this years 
305 billion defense budget and involves more than a halfmillion 
civilian and uniformed employees of the defense department 
at a news conference cheney said the evertightening defense 
budget as well as the amount of distrust in congress and among the 
public about the way the pentagon does business requires that 
something be done 
theres no silver bullet here we have a blueprint that we 
plan to pursue to try to significantly improve the way we do 
business he said 
but cheney a former member of the republican leadership in the 
house acknowledged that he wont be able to achieve changes on his 
own if were going to be successful it will be because we got 
congress to cooperate he said 
president bush requested the management report five months ago as 
part of a major review spurred on by a series of weapons procurement 
scandals defense industry employees and consultants and pentagon 
workers have been accused of improperly using confidential 
information to funnel lucrative contracts to certain manufacturers 
the elements of the package have been circulating in washington 
for some time the report already has stirred some opposition on 
capitol hill where it has been snubbed as not going far enough to 
outline details for revising the pentagons procurement practices 
the report seeks some relief from congressional oversight 
requests complaining about the staggering number of reports 
congress requires from the defense department each day 
some sections of the plan require congressional approval for 
instance the study asks that congress implement fully a biennial 
rather than annual defense budget and establish select committees 
in both houses to review and rewrite the maze of federal 
procurement laws 
many of the ideas included in the reform package were first 
proposed in the 1986 blue ribbon commission on defense management 
also known as the packard commission 
in a summary released with the report cheney said that because 
of competing national priorities the real resources available for 
defense in the early 1990s are likely to decline 
if we are to protect our global interests met our 
responsibilities and minimize the risks to our security we must 
preserve essential military capabilities through ever more skillful 
use of the resources at our disposal he said 
cheney called for better teamwork to put his initiatives into 
reality 
none represents a quick fix only an unreserved and sustained 
commitment on the part of the administration congress and industry 
will bring about real change he said 
the secretarys goal is to make clear the lines of authority in 
the procurement process not only to make it more responsive but 
also more responsible said one pentagon official speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
the proposals include 
the establishment of an executive panel to make all the major 
decisions at the defense department 
the board would be composed of the secretary the deputy 
secretary undersecretary the deputies for procurement and 
acquisitions the heads of the various services and chairman of the 
joint chiefs of staff the panel would be smaller than the current 
defense resources board which advises cheney on major weapons and 
budgetary decisions 
allowing the deputy secretary of defense to oversee the 
pentagons system for planning programming and devising its budget 
the deputy secretary would oversee the defense planning and 
resources board which also will be asked to come up with a coherent 
national defense strategy as well as a 20year road map on the 
longterm needs and investment plans for the department 
enhancing the powers of the undersecretary of defense for 
acquisition dubbed the acquisition czar the undersecretary 
would have full authority for major acquisition programs which 
would trim some of the services powers 
paring down and consolidate overlapping structures in the 
acquisition system the proposal under which cheney predicts will 
eliminate layers and functions that have no value and primarily 
through payroll cuts achieve the 30 billion in savings over the 
next four budget years 
the report notes that some 580000 civilian and military 
personnel around the world are involved in the procurement process 
the report suggests trimming the organizations on a phased basis 
by at least 15 percent by 1993 
the establishment of a defense contract managment agency to 
consolidate its contract administration activities and ride herd on 
the contracts after they have been awarded 
streamlining the defense acquisitions board which would study 
the cost and performance of weapons programs at each stage of 
development 
establishing a dedicated corps of military procurement 
specialists in each service who would be career acquisition 
specialists congress will also be asked to approve legislation to 
upgrade the salaries and training of civilian acquisition officials 
setting up an ethics council composed of the acquisitions chief 
