the action on a 33177 vote was a reaffirmation of a plan 
introduced earlier this year by treasury secretary nicholas f brady 
the reduction should be big enough to allow mexico to achieve a 
sufficiently positive rate of economic growth to ensure the 
maintenance of social and economic stability according to the 
nonbinding resolution 
the house action also urged us banking regulators the federal 
reserve board and the comptroller of the currency to make banks 
set aside more reserves for covering impaired foreign debt 
mexico and its 15 main creditor private banks said over the 
weekend that they are close to reaching an agreement in principle on 
a package that could reduce mexicos debt service costs by 3 
billion a year 
mexico asked for a 55 percent reduction in the 54 billion it 
owes private lenders about 15 billion of it to us banks after 
brady unveiled his third world debt relief plan in march 
the banks led by citicorp manufacturers hanover and chemical 
bank in new york and bank of america in san francisco have offered 
a 35 percent reduction if the world bank and international monetary 
fund guarantee interest payments on the remaining balance 
bradys plan offers private banks governmentbacked guarantees 
they will be paid interest on the remaining balance if they 
voluntarily reduce the debt third world countries owe them 
