the air force hoping to stem congressional 
opposition to the b2 bomber said tuesday that the radarevading 
aircraft outpaces 20 years of improvements in the soviet air defense 
and is key to the united states strategic force 
the estimate is the soviets have invested the equivalent of 
over 350 billion n those defenses over the 20year period and 
that investment continues the air force said in an 18page report 
released by the ranking members of the senate armed services 
committee 
that very expensive array of defenses is largely ineffective 
against an aircraft with b2 capabilities the report said 
in a closed session air force secretary donald rice and air 
force chief of staff larry welch briefed members of the senate armed 
services committee on the b2 detailing the aircrafts importance 
to the strategic forces its conventional capability and its role if 
a start agreement is reached with the soviet union 
sens sam nunn dga chairman of the panel and john warner of 
virginia ranking republican released the report 
we asked the air force to address the key issues of cost 
flight testing and the comparable worth of the b2 as the congress 
debates the defense program nunn and warner said in a onepage 
statement accompanying the report 
opposition in congress is based on the bombers pricetag 
estimated at between 500 million and 750 million a copy and the 
delay in its first flight 
the bomber moved under its own power monday when it taxied along 
a mojave desert runway it is scheduled to make its maiden flight in 
the next few weeks 18 months behind schedule 
i have serious concerns about the aircraft said senate armed 
services member john mccain rariz who attended the air force 
briefing the service must prove this aircraft before fullscale 
production 
another member of the senate panel democrat john glenn of ohio 
last month urged defense secretary dick cheney to push back 
procurement of the aircraft questioning the wisdom of buy before 
you fly 
in another step the house armed services committee slashed about 
500 million from the aircrafts procurement budget in fiscal 1990 
the pentagon has proposed spending a total of about 47 billion for 
the bomber 
one day after the runway test the air force presented its 
argument to the senate armed services panel which is in the midst 
of voting on the fiscal 1990 defense budget 
the b2 can fly through virtually unchallenged by air defense 
weapons and has the resilience to cope with the longer term 
improvements in air defenses the soviets may choose to make the 
service said 
the air force also argued that the bomber can make a powerful 
contribution with its conventional capability specifically the 
b2 can cover all the worlds land areas from three locations 
whiteman air force base in missouri diego garcia in the indian 
ocean and guam in the pacific with a single air refueling 
the air force said the b2 program is both affordable and 
essential consuming a smaller portion of the total military 
budget than either of the last two large bomber programs 
