<TEXT>
an investigating board in a report released 
tuesday said a broken metal band caused the 32 million mishap 
that damaged nasas newest wind tunnel at the langley research 
center in virginia last january 
nasa said the wind tunnel which is capable of testing models of 
advanced aircraft and spacecraft in the 600 mph to 900 mph range 
has been idled since the jan 18 accident it is being rebuilt and 
will be available for the resumption of research in november 
the metal band four feet in diameter and two feet long holds 
insulation on a fan drive shaft in the tunnel the drive shaft was 
turning at the rate of 580 rpm when the retainer broke and clamps 
were flung outward damaging all 25 fan blades 
the national transonic facility completed in 1983 is a new kind 
of wind tunnel capable of simulating aerodynamic flight conditions 
just below and above the speed of sound 
