<TEXT>
a new york congressman introduced legislation 
tuesday to ban the disposal of old batteries from cars and trucks in 
landfills and incinerators requiring motorists to take them back to 
the seller 
we need legislation to protect public health when a temporary 
drop in the price of lead discourages recycling and car batteries 
are buried or burned thus threatening the water we drink and the 
air we breathe said hochbrueckner 
when lead prices are high lead fabricators willingly buy the 
batteries from recycling firms for the 20 pounds of lead in each 
about 90 percent of all used batteries were recycled in 1980 
according to rep george hochbrueckner dny but when prices 
decline so does recycling to 66 percent in 1985 the most recent 
year for which figures are available 
us bureau of mines figures show us lead prices at almost 53 
cents per pound in 1979 43 cents in 1980 and 19 cents in 1985 
since then prices recovered to 37 cents last year peaking at 42 
cents in december before falling back to 35 cents for 1989 so far 
hochbrueckners bill would require consumers to return used car 
batteries to retailers who would be legally bound to take them the 
retailers would then have to turn the batteries over to the 
manufacturers or to recyclers 
failure to comply would be a misdemeanor with violators facing a 
maximum penalty of 30 days in jail and a 5000 fine 
a car or truck goes through several batteries in its lifetime 
often getting a new one every two or three years so the number of 
batteries discarded every year is much greater than the number of 
vehicles being junked about 70 million batteries per year 
currently 
the legislation would also require a report by the environmental 
protection agency on discarded household drycell batteries which 
can contain toxic mercury cadmium lead nickel and manganese and 
the prospects for recycling them 
under epa regulations any business that discards eight or more 
vehicle batteries per month must send them to a federally licensed 
landfill or other disposal facility if they do not recycle them 
said epa spokeswoman robin woods 
violators face civil penalties of a 25000 fine per day per 
violation and criminal sanctions of up to 50000 per day per 
violation plus a jail term of up to five years she said 
hochbrueckner said state deposit laws encouraging the recycling 
of batteries are in effect in california florida minnesota 
pennsylvania rhode island wyoming and suffolk county ny his 
bill would permit such laws to remain in effect 
</TEXT>
