<TEXT>
laurence olivier led a troupe of knights and dames 
who had illustrious stage and screen careers and his special status 
was enhanced when he gained the title of baron 
olivier who died tuesday was knighted in 1947 and elevated in 
1970 to a peerage as baron olivier of brighton the title gave him a 
seat in the house of lords which along with the house of commons 
constitutes britains parliament the only other theatrical peer is 
actor and theater founder bernard miles 
the first actor to be knighted was henry irving so honored by 
queen victoria in 1895 ellen terry his leading lady in a 
partnership that dominated the london stage for 25 years was made a 
dame in 1925 
the honors gave the profession respectability and helped 
eliminate the remains of a puritan prejudice against actors 
actors have continued to appear on the annual honors lists 
announced by buckingham palace 
donald wolfit one of this centurys great actormanagers was 
knighted in 1957 
noel coward the actor and playwright of hay fever and 
blithe spirit was knighted in 1970 and actor rex harrison was 
so honored this year 
among the other actorknights no longer living are ralph 
richardson the ebullient eccentric actor who regularly appeared 
alongside olivier and john gielgud who was knighted after world war 
ii 
