<TEXT>
britain mourned laurence olivier with tributes and 
fond memories tuesday and theaters from london to the birthplace of 
shakespeare lowered their flags and dimmed their lights 
queen elizabeth ii sent condolences to oliviers family who were 
at the actors bedside when he died peacefully at the age of 82 at 
his home in the village of ashurst 
prime minister margaret thatcher praised his extraordinary 
talents and remembered her favorite olivier roles in hamlet 
henry v and richard iii 
theaters in the west end londons equivalent of broadway dimmed 
their exterior lights for an hour 
the national theater of which olivier was a founder lowered its 
flags removed its normal playbill from its electronic billboard 
overlooking the river thames and replaced it with laurence 
olivier 19071989 
no shows were canceled however that would have been the last 
thing he would have wanted said theater spokesman stephen wood 
in two of the theaters three auditoriums leading actors from 
current productions asked the audience to stand for a moment of 
silence 
the quality of work we do here is mostly due to him veteran 
actor michael bryant told the sellout house in the nationals 
cottesloe theater following a performance of the voysey 
inheritance 
flags also were lowered at theaters in stratford birthplace of 
shakespeare whose works olivier defined for modern mass audiences 
it isnt too much to say that olivier was perhaps the greatest 
man of the theater ever said sir peter hall who followed olivier 
as artistic director of the national theater from 1973 to 1988 
larry oliviers genius shaped the last 50 years 
his genius was also recalled by three of britains famous 
actorknights interviewed by british broadcasting corp television 
sir john gielgud said in an interview from the italian city of 
siena we became in some ways kind of rivals rather than 
colleagues which i was sorry about 
but i wouldnt dream of putting myself up as a rival to him in 
talent or equipment because he had this extraordinary range of 
classical ability and comedy he was a great comedian and a very 
fine tragic actor 
sir alec guinness said he was a giant among actors 
sir john mills said he had more magic on the stage than any 
actor i have ever seen he was extraordinary he was 
irreplaceable 
rosemary harris who had several stage and screen roles opposite 
olivier said its hard to think of a world without laurence 
olivier 
some remarked on his physical courage actor anthony hopkins 
remembered his capacity to electrify people he would hurl himself 
into the role and that can be quite dangerous to limb and body he 
had tremendous athletic daring 
hopkins also praised oliviers openness to new young talents 
i remember him telling me never be afraid to be outrageous 
he said you will always be shot down in flames because people 
are going to dislike you whatever you do it is your fear of being 
criticized that stops you being outrageous 
denis quilley who acted with olivier in the 1971 production of 
eugene oneills long days journey into night recalled how 
night after night audiences would gasp in shock as olivier already 
64 threw himself backward off a table 
mickey rooney whom olivier had called the finest american actor 
said through his publicist the theater and screen will never 
again see the vision of the greatest actor who ever lived 
former president reagan said sir laurence olivier delighted 
millions with his unmatched excellence on the stage and screen 
some of the greatest moments in the history of the performing arts 
came as a result of sir laurences brilliance 
charlton heston a close friend of olivier who worked with him in 
the 1966 film khartoum said naturally im saddened but 
this represents more a resting for larry 
he was an amazingly daring actor the best of our time 
heston said from his home in los angeles i had the privilege of 
working with him on both stage and screen and his advise to me has 
proven an inestimable value 
british tv personality melvyn bragg one of the last to interview 
olivier extensively said he was as english as his own vicarage 
family a man of a thousand faces a powerful dangerous and sexy 
presence on every stage and in some memorable films 
olivier dies cried the newsbills and evening newspapers sold 
fast when rushhour commuters saw the headline 
he was a very great actor of extraordinary power said 
michael denton a physician whenever i thought of him or heard 
his name i saw his stooped figure in black as richard iii 
pat fairbairn a civil servant standing in line for a bus said 
olivier summed up the english theater he had that lovely 
dignified voice 
what impressed me was that his professional colleagues always 
spoke of him with such great respect and admiration fairbairn 
said when they played shakespeare it always seemed to me that 
they were tying to live up to olivier 
joanne james a young london actress looked crushed when she 
heard the news im sad she said hes been a symbol to 
everybody with the energy and dedication he has put into the 
theater ive grown up with him 
