the first anniversary of the crushing of prodemocracy demonstrators 
in beijings tiananmen square 
but it also would expand that order permitting the 40000 
chinese students and scholars now in the united states to remain 
through june 5 1992 unless the president certified that conditions 
had changed permitting them to return in safety before then 
the extension would apply even if the students visas had expired 
the amendment also would waive the present requirement that 
someone in the united states on a nonimmigrant visa the situation 
in which most of the chinese academic community here find themselves 
return to their homeland for two years before seeking to change 
their status to that of potential immigrant 
senate democratic leader george mitchell of maine said the 
amendment makes other changes intended to meet the concern of 
chinese students that the bush plan forced them to indicate publicly 
an unwillingness to return to chinese now 
according to the students such a statement brands them as 
traitors in the eyes of their government and provides a means for 
chinese officials to track down and pressure students who do not 
choose to return to china at this time mitchell said 
senate republican leader bob dole of kansas said the amendment 
reaffirms bushs basic position on the issue that we should not 
arbitrarily send home to a very uncertain fate the thousands of 
chinese students now studying in the united states 
dole said also that the amendment does not do violence to the 
underlying us immigration laws and does not open the gates to 
automatic citizenship for anyone 
but he said it does reflect the best of americas tradition of 
providing safe haven for those truly in danger 
the legislation does not address what might happen if it was 
clear that returning to china might endanger students and scholars 
after the june 5 1992 expiration date 
the amendment was attached to a pending bill making changes in 
us immigration law the entire package will later be considered by 
the house 
</TEXT>
