<TEXT>
born may 22 1907 in dorking southwest of london laurence kerr 
olivier was the third child of an anglican clergyman 
his first stage was at home with footlights made of tin cans at 
10 he was brutus in a school performance he donned womens clothes 
at 15 to play katherine in a stratford festival boys production of 
the taming of the shrew 
at 17 he went to birmingham to study acting a bit uncouth 
dame peggy ashcroft remembered him his hair stood on end his 
sleeves were short and he was extremely physical 
his marriage in 1930 to actress jill esmond was a disaster but 
his career took off with roles in noel cowards private lives 
and romeo and juliet where he alternated the roles of romeo and 
mercutio with john gielgud 
i had the voice larry had the legs gielgud recalled years 
later 
in 1937 olivier joined gielgud at the old vic and with ralph 
richardson formed a partnership that remade english theater all 
three were knighted after world war ii 
we became in some ways kind of rivals rather than colleagues 
which i was sorry about gielgud told the bbc on tuesday 
but i wouldnt dream of putting myself up as a rival to him in 
talent or equipment because he had this extraordinary range of 
classical ability and comedy he was a great comedian and a very 
fine tragic actor 
other actorknights of oliviers generation included guinness 
mills sir rex harrison and the equivalent among the great women of 
the stage dame ashcroft dame wendy hiller and dame judi dench 
but olivier was the only one to be elevated to the peerage 
becoming baron olivier of brighton in 1970 the title gave him a 
seat in the house of the lords the upper chamber of parliament the 
only other theatrical peer is actor and theater founder bernard 
miles 
in 1981 the queen awarded olivier the order of merit which is 
limited to 24 living members he was the only actor to hold it 
other holders include violinist sir yehudi menuhin novelist graham 
greene atomic scientist lord penney and jet engine inventor sir 
frank whittle 
oliviers stardom was assured by his move to hollywood in 1939 to 
make wuthering heights it was a towering success but also an 
invaluable lesson in acting 
he strutted around the set indulging in appalling overacting 
until director william wyler shouted what do you think you are 
doing you think you are in the opera house 
i suppose this anemic little medium cant take great acting 
olivier replied huffily the set was engulfed in laughter 
four decades later working on marathon man olivier was 
astonished that dustin hoffman had gone sleepless for two nights to 
look properly disheveled dear boy said olivier why dont 
you try acting its so much easier 
in 1939 olivier appeared with vivien leigh in a new york 
production of romeo and juliet they were married two years 
later after he divorced his first wife 
again the marriage was a debacle olivier said he once battered 
her against a wall cutting her head and nearly killing her he said 
he also considered suicide 
they were divorced in 1961 and olivier wed actress joan 
plowright with whom he finally found happiness they had a son 
richard and two daughters tamsin and juliekate all three study 
or work in the theater 
in the 1960s and 1970s olivier had scores of memorable roles 
from the fading comic archie rice in john osbornes the 
entertainer to astrov in chekhovs uncle vanya to the nazi 
who tortures dustin hoffman in marathon man 
he offended some devotees by taking cameo parts in hollywood 
potboilers but explained he needed the money 
charlton heston a close friend of olivier who worked with him in 
the 1966 film khartoum said tuesday from his home in los 
angeles that olivier was an amazingly daring actor the best of 
our time i had the privilege of working with him on both stage and 
screen and his advise to me has proven an inestimable value 
oliviers last film appearance was as an aged wheelchairbound 
war veteran in the 1988 war requiem based on the oratorio by 
composr benjamin britten 
his voice was heard publicly for the last time in a taperecorded 
contribution to save the rose theater the remnants of a theater 
where shakespeare is believed to have acted 
borrowing from the famous line he delivered in his film of 
henry v olivier said cry god for harry england and the 
rose 
</TEXT>
