<TEXT>
the government has decided that britains biggest 
brewers wont have to sell off 22000 pubs as had been recommended 
as a way of fostering competition in the nations mostly 
brewerowned taverns 
trade secretary lord young announced measures monday to encourage 
competition in the supply of beer and other drinks but they were 
not as drastic as those recommended this year by the monopolies and 
mergers commission 
britains brewers are allowed to own pubs and to require that 
their tenants only buy beer and other drinks from the owner 
industry critics have called on the government to force competition 
which would bring cheaper prices and wider choices for consumers 
lord young said brewers would be allowed to own more than 2000 
pubs each but that they would have to keep at least half of those 
above that limit as free houses which can sell beer of their 
choice 
the commission recommended in march that no brewer should be 
allowed to own more than 2000 pubs this would have meant that 
alliedlyons plc bass plc elders ixl grand metropolitan plc 
scottish and newcastle plc and whitbread plc would have had to sell 
off 22000 of their tied houses 
britain has 82000 pubs a majority of which are tied tied 
houses are either tenanted houses owned by brewers but rented to 
tenants or are managed houses which are owned and operated by the 
brewers 
young had said when the report was published that he was inclined 
to accept the commissions recommendations on thursday he met the 
brewers to discuss the report 
young speaking monday in the house of lords said his decision 
would add 11030 free houses to the existing 15000 
these proposals should enable a major freeing of the market 
without the compulsory divestment originally recommended by the 
mmc he said 
lawmaker bryan gould the opposition labor partys spokesman on 
trade matters condemned the measures as craven and complete 
capitulation of government to the big brewers 
the national consumers association said it was disappointed the 
trade secretary didnt break up the big brewers stranglehold over 
the supply of beer his compromise decision wont benefit 
drinkers it said 
the brewers society which represents britains brewing 
industry said it was studying the decision 
the tenants of the national brewers also are to be free to buy 
ciders wines and spirits as well soft drinks and low alcohol and 
nonalcoholic beer from any source young said 
young has said the commissions recommendation that tenants 
should be allowed to offer a guest beer should only apply to the 
national brewers 
the trade department said the new rules would be put in place 
following a 42day consultation period during which details of the 
regulations would be finalized 
young doesnt plan to meet with brewing industry leaders again 
the department said 
the brewers are to be given two years to implement the changes 
one year after that the director general of fair trading is to 
review the situation 
young said that the measures he had announced would involve 
significant structural changes to the market and that it was 
important to review whether they had had the effect of increasing 
competition in the brewing industry 
</TEXT>
