<TEXT>
after a trip back to the drawing board the 
securities and exchange commission is again proposing a change in 
rules that would make it easier for corporations to raise capital 
through the private sale of securities 
the commission voted unanimously 50 monday to seek another round 
of public comment on revisions to its controversial proposed rule 
144a which eliminates some restrictions on the resale of securities 
offered privately 
the secs proposed rule would create what it terms a safe 
harbor from registration and disclosure rules for the resale of 
privately offered securities to big institutional investors 
supporters of the proposed change said it would lower financing 
costs for companies and would attract foreign companies to raise 
capital in the united states 
but critics claimed the rule change would increase the power of 
large institutional investors such as banks and insurance 
companies while cutting into the business of stock exchanges 
privately sold or placed securities usually debt or equity 
securities such as corporate bonds are exempt from the secs public 
disclosure requirements 
corporations now may offer their securities in private placements 
to large investors without going through the timeconsuming 
disclosure and approval proceedings required for public offerings 
but investors who buy those disclosureexempt privately purchased 
securities must retain ownership for at least two years before they 
can be resold 
that requirement has made privately placed securities 
unattractive to many large investors 
rule 144a first proposed by the sec last october would have 
allowed the resale of such exempted or restricted securities 
providing the investors were large institutional investors with 
total assets of 100 million or more 
in response to some of the 89 letters commenting on the proposal 
as well as a roundtable discussion in march with top officials from 
major corporations and investment institutions the sec staff 
recommended changes in the original proposal 
those changes included shifting requirements on investor size 
from 100 million in total assets to 100 million in invested 
securities as a better indication of sophistication as an 
investor said linda quinn head of the secs division of 
corporation finance in a prepared statement to the five commission 
members 
one hundred million dollars in total assets is a small bank 
she said adding thats quite a small bank 
her division also recommended that the sec implement rule 144a 
in stages starting with sales to qualified institutional 
buyers with 100 million invested in securities 
also the division recommended that sellers of disclosureexempt 
privately placed securities provide the buyer upon request basic 
information concerning the issuer 
the division said it expected to return to the commission members 
with its final recommendation after more public comment early in 
the fall 
in other action the sec also proposed a rule change that would 
allow some canadian companies issuing securities to use canadian 
disclosure documents when registering in this country 
that proposal was developed in cooperation with the ontario 
securities commission and the commission des valeurs mobilieres du 
quebec 
of the 516 foreign issuers filing periodic reports with the sec 
more than half are canadian 
as of june 19 there were 21 canadian issuers listed on the new 
york stock exchange 38 on the american stock exchange and 146 
quoted on the national association of securities dealers automated 
quotations system according to the sec 
