<TEXT>
a steady decline in interest rates should prompt 
most major banks to follow chase manhattan banks lead in lowering 
the prime rate again economists predicted 
chase stood alone monday in trimming its key lending rate a half 
percentage point to 105 percent 
im a little surprised that the other banks did not come in 
with a similar decision said robert a brusca chief financial 
economist for nikko securities co international i suspect some 
key people who probably make these decisions are probably on 
vacation 
but brusca predicted others would soon follow suit this week 
even as early as today 
the prime which usually lags behind other interest rates is the 
rate banks charge customers with the best credit ratings it also is 
the benchmark rate used to set interest on a variety of consumer and 
business credit including homeequity lines of credit 
it stood at 105 percent at the start of 1989 banks raised it 
twice in february to 115 percent then lowered a half percentage 
point on june 5 those movements reflected changing concerns about 
economic growth and inflation 
economists have been predicting another primerate drop as the 
federal reserve board shows more signs of loosening its credit 
policies in response to a slowdown in economic growth and easing of 
inflation 
last week the federal funds rates the market rate of which the 
fed has direct control dipped as low as 8 percent after hovering 
at around 9 percent the federal funds rate is what banks charge 
each other for overnight loans 
other credit market rates also have been falling steadily in 
recent weeks the treasurys bellwether 30year bond for instance 
has tumbled to about 8 percent its lowest level in more than two 
years and 30year fixed mortgage rates also have fallen dropping 
last week to an average 1017 percent a 14month low according to 
hsh associates a butler njbased mortgage reserach firm 
saving rates also have slipped with the average yield on the 
sixmonth certificate of deposit down to 879 percent last week from 
from 884 percent the previous week 
bond and stock prices rose moderatly following chases 
announcement monday while the dollar was little changed to slightly 
lower 
chase said it lowered its prime rate because its cost of 
borrowing money including interest it pays on savings accounts or 
cds had declined 
last week one small bank southwest bank in st louis cut its 
prime rate to 105 percent from 11 percent but since then no major 
bank but chase has taken similar action 
although its not unusual for one or two banks to adjust their 
prime rates without others immediately following major banks have 
essentially worked in harmony in recent years 
for example citibank and chase raised their prime to 775 
percent from 75 percent on march 31 1987 a day before other major 
banks started following suit 
the last time chase went solo was on dec 28 1983 when it 
lowered the prime to 11 percent from 115 percent other banks took 
similar action two weeks later 
we made an independent judgement chase spokesman fraser 
seitel said of mondays move what we base our decisions on as 
much as anything else is the level of the cost of funds and market 
rates and at this particular level 105 percent is clearly the 
appropriate rate 
while most economists predicted that interest rates would 
continue to decline through early next year some said the lower 
rates would do little to spur the economy other than give the 
sagging housing market a lift 
i see it as more of a way of preventing a recession than 
boosting economic growth said carol a stone a senior economist 
nomura securities inc weve just been on a threetofour year 
buying surge and i think a lot of peole are saying i have my vcr 
and my camcorder and other durable goods theres not a lot of pent 
up demand here 
