<DOCNO> AP890711-0238 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
attorneys asked a delaware judge today to 
block time incs attempt to acquire warner communications inc and 
allow time shareholders to vote on a takeover bid by hostile suitor 
paramount communications inc 
in a hearing considered pivotal in the 5weekold battle for 
time attorneys for paramount maintained the media giant put itself 
up for sale when it agreed to a friendly merger with warner earlier 
this year and as such should be forced to consider paramounts 
hostile 122 billion bid 
paramount attorney melvyn l cantor told chancery court judge 
william t allen that times board knew in march when it agreed to 
merge with warner in a stock swap that the deal could put time on 
the auction block 
time subsequently changed the to a 14 billion tender offer for 
warners stock and the companies exchanged stock in each other to 
seal the deal 
cantor pointed to the exchange of stock as proof the companies 
knew they were opening themselves up to possible thirdparty bids 
michael r klein an attorney representing investor robert m 
bass and other major time shareholders made the same point 
klein said the stock exchange was done to defend the 
transactionit was understood that the market reaction might be to 
perceive that both time and warner were up for grabs 
both attorneys asked that time shareholders be allowed to vote on 
the 200 a share paramount offer time has proposed to complete the 
offer for warner without a shareholder vote 
times attorneys scheduled to present their case after a lunch 
break were expected to argue that its board never contemplated 
selling the company and that the agreement with warner stemmed from 
the ordinary conduct of times business 
nearly 200 people crowded into the chancery court for the hearing 
before judge william t allen absent were most top executives from 
the companies 
allens ruling which is not expected until later this week 
could affect more than just these three companies since many of the 
biggest us corporations are incorporated in delaware and subject 
to its laws and court rulings 
on the eve of the hearing time stock rose 112 to close at 
15262 a share monday on the new york stock exchange warner stock 
rose 25 cents to 62 a share and paramount dipped 25 cents to 5675 
a share 
time fell 262 a share to 150 in earlyafternoon trading 
today while warner lost 25 cents to 6175 and paramount rose 50 
cents to 5750 
also monday paramount said it had amended its 200pershare 
offer for time to add interest under certain conditions 
paramount said it would add interest at a rate of 9 percent a 
year if the deal were not completed within 60 days after time either 
agrees to the deal or is ordered to refrain from interfering with 
paramounts efforts to obtain government approval to transfer times 
cable television licenses 
our willingness to pay interest if the company cannot close its 
deal within 60 days underscores our confidence that regulatory 
approvals can be obtained within that period if times 
obstructionist tactics are stopped said donald oresman 
paramounts general counsel 
time offered no comment on the new terms but a source close to 
time speaking on condition he not be identified said paramounts 
interest offer represents a belated admission that it will take 
paramount a substantial period of time to obtain the necessary 
regulatory approvals 
time has rejected paramounts bid as inadequate and highly 
conditional saying it could take a year or more for paramount to 
secure the needed regulatory approvals for cable license transfers 
paramount has said it could win the necessary approvals within a 
few months but has complained that time has been drumming up 
opposition among local cable regulators to paramounts efforts 
the issue in todays court hearing according to duke university 
law school professor james d cox is whether entering into 
negotiations with warner triggers the auctioneer role for the 
time directors or can their conduct merely be judged by the 
business judgment rule 
the business judgment rule a widelyfollowed legal concept 
allows decisions made by directors in the normal course of business 
to stand courts generally are reluctant to disturb such decisions 
time chairman j richard munro hinted that the company was 
considering a merger when he told securities analysts last november 
that time intended to be among the growing ranks of global media 
conglomerates 
paramount chairman martin s davis has indicated he raised the 
possibility of a merger between paramount and time on several 
occasions during the past several years 
that raises the question of whether time entered into the merger 
agreement as a defensive step if that were the case time would be 
forced to consider buyout offers 
</TEXT>
